**Vulnerability Class:** OS Command Injection (CWE-78)

**File and Line Number:** `server.js`, Line 7

**Explanation:**
The application takes user-supplied input from the `domain` query parameter and concatenates it directly into a shell command string passed to `exec()`. Because `exec` spawns a shell, an attacker can use shell metacharacters (such as `;`, `&&`, or `|`) to terminate the intended `whois` command and execute arbitrary system commands with the privileges of the Node.js process. For example, a request to `/whois?domain=google.com; cat /etc/passwd` would result in the server leaking the system's password file.

**Proposed Fix:**
Avoid using `exec` (which invokes a shell). Instead, use `execFile` or `spawn`, which take arguments as an array and do not spawn a shell, preventing the interpretation of shell metacharacters. Additionally, implement a validation check to ensure the input conforms to an expected domain format.

```javascript
const express = require("express");
const { execFile } = require("child_process"); // Use execFile instead of exec
const app = express();

app.get("/whois", (req, res) => {
    const domain = req.query.domain;

    // Basic validation: Ensure domain exists and contains only alphanumeric/dots/hyphens
    if (!domain || !/^[a-zA-Z0-9.-]+$/.test(domain)) {
        return res.status(400).send("Invalid domain format.");
    }

    // execFile treats arguments as literal strings, not shell commands
    execFile("whois", [domain], (err, stdout) => {
        if (err) return res.status(500).send("Error retrieving whois data.");
        res.type("text/plain").send(stdout);
    });
});
```

