The regular expression `const EMAIL_RE = /^([a-zA-Z0-9]+)+@[a-zA-Z0-9]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$/;` contains nested quantifiers: `([a-zA-Z0-9]+)+`. When a regex engine encounters nested repetitions of the same character class, it can lead to "catastrophic backtracking." 

If an attacker provides a long string of alphanumeric characters that is **not** followed by an `@` symbol (e.g., `aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa!`), the engine will try every possible combination of how the characters could be grouped by the inner and outer `+` quantifiers before eventually failing. This causes the CPU usage to spike to 100%, blocking the Node.js event loop and making the server unresponsive to all other users.

